post_text:
Congratulations to our Food Service and Maintenance departments for their recognition from the Kansas State Department of Education! The honors include the Kansans Can Step Up to Lead, Kansans Can Adapt, and Kansans Can Provide Outstanding Customer Service awards, part of the state's Kansans Can 2019-2020 Best Practices Awards, which were announced Tuesday.

Our employees demonstrated incredible care and innovation and served more than 89,000 meals for our #OneMa1ze families who participated in curbside meal pickup and our summer meal program. Employees developed and used a system that provided food to those who needed it while minimizing risks associated with COVID-19.

Thank you for your outstanding practices in child nutrition!

#OneMa1zeCares

When needed, schools will have face masks available for students, as well.

post_text: Students in grades kindergarten through 12 will receive a district Chromebook to support remote learning days and full-time remote learning. Preschool students also will have a device to use. Returning secondary students will use devices already assigned to them. For other students, schools have or will communicate with parents about device distribution. Many families on the hybrid learning model will want to plan to pick up the devices during parent-teacher conferences Sept. 2 and 3. If necessary, students also could pick up their Chromebook on the first day of school. Learn more in the T4T Reopening Guide at www.usd266.com/T4TReopeningPlan.

Parents will have the option of attending conferences in-person at the school or remotely. This opportunity takes the place of Meet Your Teacher Night and back-to-school events.

This gives parents and their children an opportunity to visit the school and classroom(s) together in prescheduled small groups. Please note that morning dropoff and afternoon pickup will be curbside.

UPDATE: For full-time remote learners, parent-teacher conferences will be arranged by the teacher and may be scheduled on other days.

post_text:
Wondering about school supplies for the upcoming school year?

Students in the hybrid learning model can find their school supply lists at bit.ly/3heSiyo.

For families with children in the remote learning model: Do not purchase school supplies prior to the program start. Many homes already have the required supplies. Assigned teacher(s) will let students know what is needed.

Also, though not technically a school supply, consider adding face masks to your back-to-school shopping list. Schools will have face masks for those who need them, but families may choose to provide their own for their child(ren). They should be multi-layer. The T4T Reopening Guide defines a face mask as a "wearable, breathable covering of the nose and mouth. May be made of natural or synthetic materials and should consist of more than a single layer of material."

post_text:
We are hiring school bus drivers, van drivers, and transportation paras! Three great reasons to apply at www.usd266.com:

1. Teamwork
Be part of our amazing group of staff members dedicated to safely transporting the students of Maize USD 266.

2. Flexible schedule
Our typical schedule is 6 a.m. to 9 a.m. and 2 p.m. to 5 p.m. on school days, convenient for small business owners, college students, and those who want to be off when Maize USD 266 students are off. No evenings, weekends, or holidays. Fall Break, Winter Break, and Spring Break off.

3. Benefits
Retirement earnings through KPERS (Kansas Public Employees Retirement System), nine paid sick days a year, and $250 each month paid toward your health insurance.

Official applications must be submitted at www.usd266.com.

A reminder that you can enroll online at www.usd266.com/enrollment. Those unable to do so can attend In-Person Enrollment from noon to 7 p.m. Wednesday, July 29. Need help? Call or email: 316-350-2050 enrollment@usd266.com.

You may be aware of the news this afternoon (July 15) that Gov. Laura Kelly announced her plans to issue an executive order to delay the start of Kansas schools until Sept. 9, after Labor Day. She explained that this decision was motivated by the increasing number of COVID-19 cases throughout the state and related effects on hospitals.

At this time, a delayed start would not change the required number of hours for students to be in school, a requirement set by the Kansas Legislature.

Please visit bit.ly/DelayedStart to read a message from Dr. Chad Higgins, Superintendent of Schools, to learn more about next steps and how a delayed school start affects Maize USD 266.

Instead, the district will celebrate the Class of 2020 in a different way that will allow students and their families to recognize graduates, take photos, and make memories.

Additional details will be forthcoming and sent to Class of 2020 graduates and their parents early next week (the week of July 13, 2020).

post_text:
Have you seen Maize USD 266 buses in your neighborhood and wonder why?

The Maize Transportation Department is working to implement a new system that will provide improved safety and real-time management of the passengers, drivers, and bus fleet. Part of the process with the new Transportant system is for school bus drivers to physically drive each bus a few times on its normal school day route. Driving the route, including stopping at designated bus stops, allows the computer’s GPS system to create a map that will be used by drivers and substitute drivers daily. During this calibration period, you likely will see Maize school buses in your neighborhood. Drivers will not be picking up passengers.

Work is scheduled to begin Monday, May 11 to the intersection of 119th Street and 45th Street North, which will be closed to traffic for a majority of the summer.

Please note that all 45th Street entrances to Maize High School will be closed at that time. Anyone needing to access Maize High School during that period must do so by entering the parking lot by the baseball and softball fields from the north. Road closures are indicated in yellow on the accompanying map.

Bond projects will add a new intermediate school to the northwest corner of 45th and 119th streets in Maize and the new aquatorium pool-auditorium center to the southeast corner of Academy Avenue and 119th Street.

These upgrades prepare for those changes and the extra traffic they will bring.

Work is scheduled to be finished by Aug. 10. School for 2020-21 is scheduled to begin on Aug. 11.

For more information on Grab and Go breakfasts and lunches, please visit the district website by clicking here. https://www.usd266.com/Page/4926

It's Census Day! The 2020 Census count taking place now is the once-a-decade population count that leads to numbers used to distribute more than $6 billion in federal funds to Kansans every year.

Federal dollars at stake for the community include those tied to title programs, the National School Lunch Program, career and technical education grants, the Federal Pell Grant Program, and other programs that support our students and their families. Everyone can participate online, by phone, or by mail to ensure an accurate count and appropriate funding.

Learn more about the 2020 U.S. Census at 2020census.gov.

#OneMa1ze

March 23 at 9:20 AM ·

The Maize Education Foundation sad to announce that this year's Spring Breakfast event is "officially" cancelled as part of the community's efforts to flatten the exposure curve and prevent the spread of covid-19. We've also made the difficult decision not to reschedule for 2020, but are looking into dates for Spring 2021.

We would like to take this time to thank our Maize USD 266 school-community, our many sponsors who have shown so much support, our educators who are tirelessly working to make remote learning a reality, and our parents who will be instrumental in making so many new things possible.

#OneMa1zeStrong #OneMa1zeCares

post_text:
Parents, here are some tips to make sure you receive e-mails sent from Maize USD 266:

The district uses ConnectEd, a mass communication tool by BlackBoard, to communicate with our patrons. Because it is a mass communication tool, e-mail services like Cox, Gmail, Hotmail, Outlook and Yahoo! Mail may block e-mail to protect you from unwanted or malicious e-mails such as phishing, scams, and spam. In this case, they are mistaking e-mails that you want for e-mail that you don't want. Parents may have to "Whitelist" or add us as a Safe Sender in order to keep it from filtering it out. In order to do this, please add NoReply@blackboard.com to your Safe Sender list.

post_text:
While school buildings across Kansas are closed during the Coronavirus outbreak, school breakfasts and lunches are still available. Beginning on Wednesday, March 25, Maize USD 266 will offer free grab-and-go breakfasts and lunches on Mondays and Wednesdays at two locations in the district.

Food Service staff members will distribute meals from their station at the complex front office entrance and deliver straight to your car. No need to get out!

Please RSVP at https://forms.gle/fZuD44unKgL27omX9 or visit the district website for more information: https://www.usd266.com/Page/4926

Meals are free to all students regardless of income. No income-related questions will be asked. Special arrangements can be made for quarantined families or for children with dietary restrictions. Currently, we plan to provide meals in this way until the last day of school, scheduled for May 20, or until otherwise notified.

#OneMa1ze
#OneMa1zeCares

post_text:
Congratulations to Maize High School junior Hannah Soderstrom, finalist in the Prudential Spirit of Community Awards, which recognize outstanding youth volunteers.

Hannah, pictured with her parents Heather and Scott Soderstrom, was nominated by the American Red Cross of South Central Kansas because of her passion for blood drives and blood donations after benefiting from them personally via blood transfusions after her leukemia diagnosis in 2016.

Hannah, now a cancer survivor, is an advocate for blood donations and has hosted five blood donation drives, which collected more than 250 units of blood.

American Red Cross The Prudential Spirit of Community Awards

In an effort to maintain and promote safe and healthy schools, Maize USD 266 has increased communication to educators and students this week regarding the importance of proper and frequent handwashing. One of the best and easiest ways to keep you and our school healthy is for each of us to wash our hands carefully, especially after bathroom breaks and before snacks and meals.

District leaders are asking parents and families to join in this effort. Please review the five steps for proper handwashing from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) at https://www.cdc.gov/handwashing/when-how-handwashing.html.

Thank you for helping us stay healthy together as #OneMa1ze!

#OneMa1zeCares

post_text:
Maize USD 266 takes very seriously the health of our students and employees. District leaders, school administrators, and school nurses are working together in the best interest of the health of students and employees. As needed, leaders will work with professionals at the Sedgwick County Government Health Department, Kansas Department of Health and Environment (KDHE), Kansas State Department of Education (KSDE), and other public health and educational agencies to make the best decisions possible for schools in the event of any issue.

In an effort to continue to stay vigilant during the remainder of cold and flu season and in light of the rapidly developing Coronavirus situation, district leaders are sharing reminders and updates on a district webpage dedicated to Coronavirus COVID-19 prevention and information, accessible by clicking the link below.

#OneMa1ze
#OneMa1zeCares

"In a perfect world, our schools would be funded as they are needed. The Foundation provides resources for our students and our staff that we wouldn't have otherwise."

Thank you to MEF Board Member Julie Eastlick for your work and commitment to the Maize Education Foundation and the students and staff of Usd 266-Maize.

If you would like to learn more about the Maize Education Foundation and how you can help us in our mission, visit www.maizeeducationfoundation.org. There are many ways to help and so many reasons!

post_text:
Dr. Jeff Jarman, Maize Board of Education President, and his fellow board members on Jan. 13 celebrated Maize High School journalism students who earned national recognition for their work.

A story by senior Abby McCoy and 2019 graduate Ryann Redinger placed second in the nation for a story they co-wrote about the dangers of electronic smoking devices. Redinger is doing missions work overseas and could not attend the meeting, so her mother Jessica Pohlman and stepfather Dylan Pohlman attended on her behalf.

Senior Sam Bartlett was honored for his Honorable Mention in the Sports Action Photo of the Year category.

#OneMa1ze
